Digital Elevation Model of New Orleans, Louisiana

NOAA has developed an integrated bathymetric-topographic digital elevation model (DEM) of the New Orleans, LA area to support the modeling of coastal processes. The DEM covers the area surrounding New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain, with coordinate boundaries 90.65° to 89.3° W and 29.70° to 30.50° N. at 1/3 arc-second cell size (~10 meters). It is referenced to a horizontal datum of North American Datum of 1983 (NAD 83), and one of three vertical datums: North American Vertical Datum of 1988 (NAVD 88), Mean High Water (MHW) or Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW).

The New Orleans DEM and supporting documentation are available on the project web site: http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/inundation/vdatum/vdatum.html

The NOAA VDatum DEM Project was funded by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) of 2009 (http://recovery.gov).

Digital Elevation Model of Mobile, Alabama

NOAA has developed an integrated bathymetric-topographic digital elevation model (DEM) of the Mobile, AL area to support the modeling of coastal processes. The DEM covers the area surrounding Mobile Bay, with coordinate boundaries 88.3° to 87.65° W and 30.0° to 31.0° N at 1/3 arc-second cell size (~10 meters). It is referenced to a horizontal datum of North American Datum of 1983 (NAD 83), and one of two vertical datums: North American Vertical Datum of 1988 (NAVD 88) or Mean High Water (MHW).

The Mobile DEM and supporting documentation are available on the project web site: http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/inundation/vdatum/vdatum.html

The NOAA VDatum DEM Project was funded by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) of 2009 (http://recovery.gov).

Digital Elevation Model of Biloxi, Mississippi

NOAA has developed an integrated bathymetric-topographic digital elevation model (DEM) of the Biloxi, MS area to support the modeling of coastal processes. The DEM covers Biloxi and offshore areas, with coordinate boundaries 89.3° to 88.3° W and 29.7° to 30.6° N at 1/3 arc-second cell size (~10 meters). It is referenced to a horizontal datum of World Geodetic System of 1984 (WGS 84) and a vertical datum of Mean High Water (MHW).

The Biloxi DEM and supporting documentation are available on the project web site: http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/inundation/tsunami/inundation.html
